Jason: Variance between Claude and Codex. Claude Code spins up its own lane agents
and manages them in its own session — fan-out works really well; Codex has nothing
like it (at the time). I tried to create sub-worktrees in the agents platform so
you could have agents per worktree, but if you're using Claude you don't need that
— Claude spins up its own lane agents inside its process and manages them, with
eventing (when lane agent X finishes, the controller outer-loop agent is notified).
With separate tmux/SSH sessions the outer agent has to poll them. Sub-worktrees are
too complicated; letting Claude do it is the better solution because it evolves
with Claude. The agents-platform sub-worktree machinery effectively becomes
pointless once you have Claude fan-out. As it stands you need one Claude Code
session and can run all the layers of the loop within it.

